      "description": "Advanced course in game theory provides rigorous overview of equilibrium concepts for non-cooperative games in static and dynamic settings. Covers iterated strict dominance, rationalizability, Nash equilibrium, subgame perfection, sequential, perfect and proper equilibria, the intuitive criterion, and iterated weak dominance. Applications to auctions, bargaining, and repeated games. Introduces solution concepts for cooperative games and their non-cooperative implementations, as well as matching theory.",
